Sure! Here's a trader-focused breakdown of each signal — no code, pure logic and concept.

***

## SuperEngulfing

The idea is that **big engulfing candles reveal institutional intent**. When a candle sweeps beyond the previous candle's range and closes strongly, it means smart money grabbed the liquidity sitting at those highs/lows (stop losses, pending orders) and then pushed price in their direction.[^7_1]

**REV (Reversal)** is the more powerful signal. For example a bullish REV means: the market was bearish, the new candle dipped below the previous red candle's low (grabbed sell-side liquidity), but then completely reversed and closed above the previous candle's open. Bulls fully took control in a single candle.[^7_1]

**RUN (Continuation)** means the trend is so strong that even after grabbing liquidity against it, price snaps back and continues. For example in a bull trend, price briefly dips below the previous candle's low (trapping late sellers), then closes higher than the previous close — the dip was fake, trend resumes.[^7_1]

**Plus variants** are even more aggressive — the candle doesn't just engulf the body, it closes beyond the entire wick. This means there was zero ambiguity, price completely dominated the previous candle's full range.[^7_1]

> ✅ This signal is **solid** conceptually. The only thing to verify is whether the scanner is catching it on **closed candles only** (it is — it slices off the last forming candle).[^7_1]

***

## ICT Daily Bias

This is about **knowing which pool of liquidity the market is targeting next**. Every candle creates a range — a high and a low. When the next candle **closes outside** that range, institutions have shown their hand: they broke the prior structure to grab liquidity and will now drive price toward the opposite side.[^7_1]

Concretely:

- If yesterday's candle closed **below** the day-before's low → bearish bias. The market grabbed buy-side stops below, now it's heading lower to take sell-side liquidity.[^7_1]
- If yesterday's candle closed **above** the day-before's high → bullish bias. The market grabbed sell-side stops above, now it's heading higher.[^7_1]

The `prevHigh` and `prevLow` lines on the chart are essentially the **targets** — price is expected to at least reach those levels during the session.

> ⚠️ One thing to watch: this is a **lagging bias** — it's based on the previous closed candle. By the time you see the signal, price may already be well into the move. The Live Bias recalculation every 60 seconds helps keep this fresh, but on lower timeframes like 4H it can still be slow to update.[^7_1]

***

## RSI Divergence

This is a **momentum exhaustion detector**. The logic is: price and RSI should move together. When they disagree — price goes one way but RSI goes the other — it means the move is losing fuel even if price looks strong on the surface.[^7_1]

**Regular divergences** are reversal signals:

- Price drops to a new low but RSI makes a higher low → sellers are losing strength, a bounce is likely
- Price rises to a new high but RSI makes a lower high → buyers are exhausted, a drop is likely[^7_1]

**Hidden divergences** are continuation signals:

- Price makes a higher low (pullback in an uptrend) but RSI makes a lower low → the pullback is weak, uptrend resumes
- Price makes a lower high (bounce in a downtrend) but RSI makes a higher high → the bounce is weak, downtrend resumes[^7_1]

The RSI zone filter (must be below 30 for bullish, above 70 for bearish) is a **quality gate** — it ensures you're only catching divergences at actual extremes, not random mid-range wiggles.[^7_1]

> ⚠️ Two things to verify here:
> 1. **Hidden divergences are often misunderstood** — they look "wrong" visually because RSI moves opposite to what you'd expect. Make sure the UI labels them clearly as continuation vs reversal so users don't trade them backwards.
> 2. The pivot lookback of **5 bars left + 5 bars right** means a signal is only confirmed **5 bars after** the actual pivot. On 1H that's a 5-hour delay. Traders need to know this so they don't expect real-time pivot detection.[^7_1]

***

