Great question. Here's a simple visual explanation:

## How Pivot Lookback Works

A pivot low is only **confirmed** when the system has seen enough bars on **both sides** of it to be sure it's a real low point. With `lbL = 5, lbR = 5` it means:[^9_2]

- 5 bars to the **left** must all be higher than the pivot
- 5 bars to the **right** must all be higher than the pivot

Only then is it called a confirmed pivot.[^9_7]

```
Bar:  1    2    3    4    5  [PIVOT]  7    8    9   10   11
RSI: 45   42   38   35   32   [^9_28]   31   34   37   40   43
                                ↑
                         Only confirmed here,
                         after bar 11 closes
```

So at the moment bar 6 (the actual low) forms, **you don't know yet** it's a pivot. You only know it's a pivot after 5 more bars close and all of them are higher. That's the delay.[^9_2]

## In Real Time Terms

| Timeframe | Delay (5 bars) |
| :-- | :-- |
| 1H | ~5 hours |
| 4H | ~20 hours |
| 1D | ~5 days |

This means on the **1H timeframe**, by the time your scanner confirms a divergence, the price pivot happened **5 hours ago**. The signal is still valid — it's a confirmed setup — but the entry point may have already moved significantly.[^9_16]

## What This Means for Your Product

This is not a bug, it's just the nature of pivot-based detection. The key thing is to **set the right expectation for users** — RSI Divergence signals are **confirmed setups**, not real-time alerts. The trader still needs to find their entry after the signal fires, not blindly enter at the signal price.

> And good call on dropping hidden divergences — regular divergences are cleaner, easier to explain, and more straightforward to trade. Hidden ones require much more context to act on correctly.
